The new anti-globalization reaction
PRINCETON – A palpable sense of unease was felt during the last G-7 summit in Ise-Shima, Japan.
At the next meeting of the world's major developed economies' leaders, no one can say which of them will be among the populist insurgents.
President Donald Trump could represent the United States, or President Marine Le Pen could represent France.
They could sit with British Prime Minister Boris Johnson, Italian Prime Minister Beppe Grillo, or even with German Chancellor Frauke Petry.
Each of them could become the champion of nationalism and isolationism, in one form or another.
The reaction against globalization has lasted for two decades.
At the end of the 20th century, the global trend seemed to be convergence and people seemed to consume the same products everywhere.
McDonald's illustrated this kind of globalization: smashing the stores of this chain has become a standard form of protest against globalization.
But recently, the nature of globalization has changed, as has the reaction against it.
Although the world is becoming increasingly interconnected, there is a feeling that we understand foreigners less.
In response to the evolution of consumer preferences (which are increasingly specific), companies are relocating their production closer to the markets where the goods will be sold.
This weakens the growth of international trade.
Such "on-shore" anchoring is not new.
In the 1970s and 1980s, Americans feared that the United States would be flooded by Japanese cars. They then began producing these cars domestically.
Currently, most of the "Japanese" cars sold in the United States are made in the United States. However, reversing the globalization of goods is now easier than ever, thanks to advances in robotic engineering and the development of processes such as 3D printing.
Thus, the current critique of globalization tends to focus less on trade issues.
But this evolution reflects not only the slowdown in the growth of trade.
Consumers in wealthy countries are much more comfortable with foreign products, and in some cases even dependent on them, from constantly updated electronics to "fast fashion" at low prices, which has become predominant in advanced economies.
Instead of rejecting foreign products, today's opponents of globalization reject foreigners.
The disputes over investor protection clauses in trade agreements such as the Trans-Pacific Partnership or the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership focus on the issues of obscure courts protecting the interests of foreign companies and supposedly undermining national sovereignty.
Then comes the global refugee crisis: in Europe, in particular, the anxiety over this influx may be a precursor to a broader rejection of immigration from failing and impoverished states.
Why are the populations of advanced countries so afraid of foreigners?
This is not as if they had never been exposed to other cultures.
Many citizens of these countries constantly travel to distant destinations and hundreds of millions of people around the world head each year toward advanced countries.
The problem lies in the way we travel.
Today, we are more likely to experience things quickly and superficially, rather than to immerse ourselves in a culture.
But as modern game theory teaches us, a single interaction is very different from continuous contact.
If participants know they have a unique and limited experience, they have no interest in building a deeper base of understanding or cooperation.
Continuous exchange is necessary to foster trust.
The result of the superficial approach of current travel is evident for any major tourist destination.
Restaurants are unlikely to provide good or even honest service to people who surely will never come back.
Restaurants serve mediocre (or worse) food without a smile, taxi drivers cheat you, hoteliers lie about their facilities.
Moreover, this little game can be interrupted.
On sites where tourism has become a source of foreign revenue, it has also become a tempting target for terrorists who base their ideology on anti-Western resentment.
Some attacks in places like Bali or the Red Sea tourist complexes are enough to cause deep economic destabilization.
Tourism companies respond to such risks by minimizing contact with the local population.
The emblem of modern tourism is a gigantic cruise ship, where passengers can spend a few hours at each destination (to visit a magnificent Caribbean island or an ancient Mediterranean port), but always sleep in the same bed.
The new ship Harmony of the Seas by Royal Caribbean aims to reproduce all the climates of the world.
In fact, this ship, which is more than 30 meters long than the Eiffel Tower, contains a tropical park and an ice rink (in addition to its 23 pools and 42 bars).
Tourist bus or train companies do the same to ensure the safety of their clients, releasing them onto a famous site only for a limited time, in fact just long enough to take a few photos.
This style of travel exerts a constraint on the capacity of local infrastructure.
There is often not enough space to walk along the canals of Venice or on the path leading to the Acropolis.
This approach reinforces mutual misunderstanding.
Visitors remain within the limits of their pre-planned excursions, encountering only swindlers who offer trinkets or overpriced taxi rides.
The indigenous people do not particularly appreciate tourist groups gathering around their most beautiful sites.
No one feels particularly involved, nor maintains any relationship of trust.
It is easy to feel some nostalgia for the time when tourism went hand in hand with long stays and long-term encounters with very different cultures.
It would obviously be impossible, given the current number of visitors, to stay for weeks or months in ancient monasteries.
But it is possible to imagine certain configurations in which visitors and their hosts could interact in a more personal way.
Airbnb, for example, can provide a much more attractive experience than a hotel, or worse, than a cruise ship.
Is there an equivalent policy to Airbnb?
Could world leaders participate in summits like the G-7, living and working for an extended period of time in a foreign country?
Shortly after the United States entered the war during World War II, Winston Churchill made this famous gesture of lifting camp to stay at the White House for 24 days, in order to strengthen the transatlantic alliance of Great Britain, deepening his relationship with Franklin Roosevelt.
This level of familiarity could well be the greatest enemy of today's anti-globalization populists.
